      "text": "## Expedited Resource Addition Study\n\nAn overview of how the Expedited Resource Addition Study (ERAS) process will be implemented and the requirements for completing an ERAS application.\n\n### What is ERAS?\n\nThe Expedited Resource Addition Study (ERAS) is the temporary process for expediting the study and approval of interconnection projects needed for resource adequacy and/or reliability needs.\n\nMISO has proposed the Expedited Resource Addition Study process to expedite the approval of new generation needed to address the region’s resource adequacy and reliability needs. It is a short-term solution with strict eligibility requirements. MISO filed the refined ERAS proposal on June 6, 2025. FERC issued its Order accepting MISO’s refined ERAS filing on June 21, 2025.\n\nTiming\n\n• ERAS will commence on the requested effective date of August 6, 2025. o MISO will begin accepting ERAS application submittals in the online application portal on August 6, 2025, at 8:00:00 AM EST (9:00:00 EDT / 8:00:00 CDT). Applications received any time before 8:00:00 AM EST will not be automatically rejected but will be moved back to \"Initiated\" status manually. Once the application is moved back into \"Initiated\" status, it may be submitted again by the IC. This could affect the application's placement in the ERAS queue. \n\n• ERAS will sunset on the earlier of the completion of the 68 th Interconnection Request (IR) ERAS study or on August 31, 2027.\n\nInherent Access Limitations • Localized resource adequacy needs and the generator’s ability to meet that need\n\n• Strict eligibility requirements due at the time of ERAS application submittal, along with all other requirements applicable to IRs processed through the queue, include: 100% generator and Interconnection Customer Interconnection Facility (ICIF) site control, Relevant Electric Retail Rate Authority (RERRA) verification, off-take agreement, a non refundable $100,000 entry D1 application fee, full Network Resource Interconnection Service (NRIS), a Commercial Operation Date (COD) no later than three years from submission date, and the Generating Facility must be within the same LRZ as the identified need (unless an exception is submitted). Additionally, the requested interconnection service must not exceed 150% of the identified MW need. \n\n### ERAS Application Submission Overview\n\nERAS applicants must submit the following items and information at the time of application submission. Unless marked recommended, an application missing one of these items will be deemed deficient.\n\n• Completed Appendix 1 o Section 4s must include: ▪ Requested carve out (if applicable) ▪ Transfer project declaration (if applicable) \n\n▪ Description of resource adequacy or reliability need ▪ Information pertaining to the LRZ requirement ▪ Information pertaining to the size requirement\n\n• RERRA Verification (for projects not serving retail load)\n\n• Off-take agreement • Payment (D1, D2, M2)\n\n• PSCAD models (recommended)\n\n• Proof of initiated Market Participant registration (recommended) for applicants in JTIQ region\n\n### ERAS Cycles, Caps, Carve Outs, & Application Deadlines\n\nERAS Interconnection Requests can be submitted and compiled for study after the effective date. Projects are studied on a first-come, first-served basis. Kickoff for each project is determined by submission time.\n\nERAS Project Cap and Carve Outs\n\n• MISO will study no more than 68 ERAS projects total until the sunset date of August 31, 2027. o Of the 68 projects, MISO has carved out a maximum of 8 ERAS IRs to serve retail choice load. ▪ These projects must address retail choice load, which is currently located in Illinois and approximately 10% of Michigan. o Of the 68 projects, MISO has carved out 15 ERAS IRs for Independent Power Producers (IPPs) with agreements with entities other than Load Serving Entities (LSEs). ▪ IPPs meeting all requirements and having an agreement with or without an LSE will still qualify for the remaining 50 ERAS IRs under the total 68 project cap. ▪ Any ERAS IRs submitted by IPPs that do not involve an LSE will be first counted towards the 15 ERAS IRs cap for IPPs. After those 15 ERAS IRs for IPPs-only have been fulfilled, any subsequent ERAS IR submitted by an IPP will be counted toward the remaining 50 ERAS IRs. o ERAS applicants must indicate in Section 4.s of Appendix 1 that they are requesting a carve out, if applicable. \n\n#### ERAS Study Cycles\n\n• There are four ERAS study periods in each year with the following start and end dates: o Quarter 1: The first business day of March through the last business day of May o Quarter 2: The first business day of June through the last business day of August o Quarter 3: The first business day of September through the last business day of November o Quarter 4: The first business day of December through the last business day of February \n\n• MISO will study no more than 15 projects per ERAS quarterly study period. o Each quarter could include, but is not guaranteed to include, projects from each carve out.\n\no Projects will be studied on a first-come, first-served basis, taking into consideration their application review \nresults, which involves ensuring the projects meet the ERAS requirements and are not located within the \nsame geographic area as another project submitted for the same study period. \n▪ The study order is determined by the time stamp on their application in the online application tool \nand if their application is accepted during that ERAS study period review. \n▪ If more than 15 ERAS IRs are submitted for one ERAS study period, those surpassing the limit will be \ndeferred to be studied in a future study cycle in the order in which they were submitted. \no If multiple ERAS IRs are submitted during the same study period and within a similar geographic area – such \nthat they affect the same constraint(s) – the application submitted first will be processed in the upcoming \nquarterly cycle and the second will be deferred to a future study cycle. \n▪ Common Constraint Analysis Overview \n• The common constraint analysis is a DC screen MISO utilizes. TARA is used to mimic the injections with a DC screen at approximately 75% and a 5% DFAX threshold. \n• The DFAX threshold is based on qualifying as an impactful project that can meet cost allocation criteria, and the margin of the loading is intended to provide leeway between the triage model and the actual trued‑up study model, including GIA generator inclusion and EPR inclusion considerations. o If multiple projects are proposed to address the same load, those projects will be distributed across future ERAS study periods in the order in which they were submitted. \n• MISO will queue IRs by their submission time. If, during the application review, one of the 15 selected projects is found to be ineligible for study, MISO will select the next queued project for review, taking into consideration the requested carve out and whether it is in the same geographic location as a project currently in the study period. o If one of the 15 projects in an ERAS study cycle drops out after kickoff, MISO will not screen another project to take its place in that cycle. \n\nERAS Application Deadlines\n\n• Applications for each quarter will be due no later than 15 business days prior to study kickoff for the quarter. o Application deadlines and kickoff dates will be publicized on the MISO website under the Expedited Resource Addition Study (ERAS) tab. o The application portal will not close. o The first quarterly study will kick off on September 2, 2025; therefore, applications for the first quarterly study period must be received by August 11, 2025. o The final application deadline for the ERAS process is May 10, 2027. \n• If on August 31, 2027, MISO has received more than 68 ERAS IRs, then the projects that came in over the cap will go through the standard withdrawal process. Each applicant will lose their D1 payment (non-refundable application fee of $100,000) and be refunded the re",
