      "text": "1\nUNITED STATES OF AMERICA\nBEFORE THE\nFEDERAL ENERGY REGULATORY COMMISSION\nMidcontinent Independent\nSystem Operator, Inc.\n)\n)\n)\nDocket No. ER25-1674-000\nPROTEST OF PUBLIC INTEREST ORGANIZATIONS\nI. Introduction\nPursuant to Rule 211 of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission’s (“FERC” or \n“Commission”) Rules of Practice and Procedure,1 Clean Wisconsin, Fresh Energy, Natural \nResources Defense Council, Sierra Club, Sustainable FERC Project, and Union of Concerned \nScientists, together Public Interest Organizations (“PIOs”), submit this protest to the proposed \ntariff revisions that Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (“MISO”) filed with the \nCommission on March 17, 2025, comprising its Expedited Resource Addition Study (“ERAS”) \nprocess.\n2\nAt its heart, the ERAS proposal is a queue-jumping mechanism for preferred projects. In \nMISO’s own telling, such a proposal is necessitated by MISO’s failure to maintain a process that \ntimely processes interconnection requests from new generation. And as a result of this failure, \nMISO now claims that it needs to create a separate interconnection process to ensure that these \npreferred projects are able to come online by the time they are needed for grid reliability. \nHowever, notably absent from this story is any technical quantification of MISO’s need, or any \ndiscussion of how the ERAS process will deliver needed generation any faster than \n1 18 C.F.R. § 385.211 (2024). 2 Midcontinent Indep. Sys. Operator, Inc., Revisions to the Open Access Transmission, Energy and Operating \nReserve Tariff: Expedited Resource Addition Study, Docket No. ER25-1674-000 (Mar. 17, 2025) (“ERAS \nTransmittal Letter”), Accession No. 20250317-5212.\n2 \ncomprehensive reforms of the general interconnection process, some of which are already \nunderway and have yet to come fully to fruition. \nThese absences are telling, and should raise alarm bells for the Commission, because the \nERAS proposal runs directly contrary to the long-standing open access protections that all \ntransmission owners and operators are required to follow and the Commission is required to \nenforce. While standard operation rules may need to be—and sometimes are—set aside to \naddress true emergencies, they should never be treated lightly and should be narrowly tailored to \nminimize any deviation from open access norms. \nUnfortunately, the ERAS proposal fails this bar. After identifying a poorly defined\nresource adequacy “emergency,” MISO sets forth a highly disruptive secondary interconnection \nprocess, creates massively discriminatory eligibility provisions to give load-serving entities near\u0002exclusive access to it, and then structures its new process so that it poses a significant risk of \nimposing higher interconnection costs and slower interconnection timelines on MISO’s existing \ninterconnection customers, as well as affected load. MISO then gives the keys to this exclusive \ninterconnection “VIP” process to states with every incentive to push as many projects into ERAS\nas possible—and almost no oversight over how the states determine which projects qualify for \nERAS, or whether they address true emergency reliability or resource adequacy needs. At the \nsame time, states with retail supply competition are excluded from participation. And unlike its \npeer Regional Transmission Organizations (“RTOs”), who have proposed or are developing one\u0002time emergency processes,3 MISO somehow tries to justify running this exclusionary queue\u00023 See, e.g., CAISO Cal. Indep. Sys. Operator Corp., 180 FERC ¶ 61,143, at P 42 (2022) (“CAISO Emergency \nProcess Order”); PJM Interconnection, LLC, 190 FERC ¶ 61,084 (2025) (“RRI Order”); Southwest Power Pool \nResource and Energy Adequacy Leadership Meeting Materials for April 2, 2025 (Mar. 26, 2025), \nhttps://spp.org/spp-documents\u0002filings/?document name=REAL&docket=&start=&end=&filter filetype=&search type=filtered search. \n3\njumping process every quarter for the better part of four years. And as a final insult to the \nexisting interconnection procedure, MISO then declines even to require that these “emergency” \nprojects achieve commercial operation any faster than could be achieved going through the \nregularly scheduled interconnection processes.\nWhere true emergencies arise, it is of course within the purview and responsibility of \nRTOs to respond—and to, at times, even temporarily set aside the core fairness and \nnondiscrimination standards that normally guide RTO and Commission policymaking. But \nMISO has not adequately supported its claim that such an emergency is upon us; and in any \nevent its proposed solution is overly broad, unduly discriminatory, and insufficiently tailored to \nmeet the emergency it has claimed. The Commission should reject MISO’s ERAS proposal for \nall of these reasons, as explained further below.\nII. Background\nMISO proposes ERAS as a separate process from the standard Generator Interconnection \nQueue that, rather than being studied and allocated costs as part of a cluster, will be studied \nserially on a quarterly basis.4 This separate ERAS interconnection process offers a number of \nbenefits for any selected project over the standard queue, including quick processing time—\ngranting an Expedited Generator Interconnection Agreement (“EGIA”) in just 90 days compared \nto the median duration of almost 40 months for IAs executed in MISO between 2018 and 2023,5\nand the one year timeframe under MISO’s “timeline reduction” filing6—and its separate study \n4 ERAS Transmittal Letter at 4.\n5 Joseph Rand et al., Queued Up: 2024 Edition, Characteristics of Power Plants Seeking Transmission \nInterconnection As of the End of 2023, Lawrence Berkeley Nat’l Lab’y, at slide 35 (Apr. 2024) (“Queued Up \n2024”), https://emp.lbl.gov/queues. 6 ERAS Transmittal Letter at 36 (citing Midcontinent Indep. Sys. Operator, Inc., 178 FERC ¶ 61,141 (2021)).\n4\nmethod, which is less likely to have to contribute to the cost of shared upgrades and enjoys the \nbenefit of having any unresolved impact costs be paid directly by load. \nMISO states that ERAS seeks projects that are “shovel ready,” but MISO’s definition of \nthis seems to vary. At times, MISO states that it seeks projects that are commercially viable in \nfive years—and at other times in three to six years—while allowing projects that, with the \ndefault extension, would be completed in the end of 2032, or seven years.7 Projects applying to \nERAS in 2025 and 2026 could choose a commercial operation date (“COD”) up to three years \nout from the date of application, plus will be allowed another three years’ extension to their \nCOD,\n8 while projects applying to ERAS in 2027 and 2028 face a commercial operation deadline \nof December 31, 2028, again with the possibility of another three years’ extension. As a result of \nthis treatment, projects applying in the 2026 cycles would not need to be completed until the end \nof 2032.\nMr. Witmeier states that “MISO understands the concerns that ERAS is enabling queue \njumping,” but argues that it has limited eligibility for ERAS to select shovel ready projects.9\nHowever, there is no cap on how many projects nor megawatts can apply to, or be selected \nthrough, the ERAS process.10 Instead, MISO proposes several criteria for ERAS eligibility. \nSome of these criteria (e.g. site control, deposits, and milestone payments) resemble the sort of \nmeasures Order No. 2023 requires of standard interconnection processes in order to ensure \nreadiness and deter speculative requests and withdrawals.11\n7 ERAS Transmittal Letter at 21. \n8 Id. 9 ERAS Transmittal Letter, Prepared Direct Testimony of Andy Witmeier at 16:7–11 (“Witmeier Testimony”). 10 ERAS Transmittal Letter at 22. 11 Id. at 4, 21.\n5\nThe other two criteria are unique to ERAS: projects must be submitted with a written \nnotification from a Relevant Electric Retail Regulatory Authority (“RERRA”) that the ERAS \nproject is needed “to meet a resource adequacy and/or reliability need”12, and must demonstrate \nt",
